---
# PPSK (Private Pre-Shared Key) Profiles
#
# PPSK allows different passwords to assign devices to different VLANs on the same SSID.
# This is useful for multi-tenant networks, device segmentation, or temporary access.

ppsk_profiles:
  # Example: Home network with VLAN names (RECOMMENDED)
  - name: "Home-PPSK"
    entries:
      - name: "Trusted-Devices"
        psk: "TrustedPass123!"
        vlan: "Trusted"  # VLAN name from infra_networks.yml (recommended)
      - name: "IoT-Devices"
        psk: "IoTPass123!"
        vlan: "IoT"  # VLAN name from infra_networks.yml (recommended)
      - name: "Guest-Access"
        psk: "GuestPass123!"
        vlan: "30"  # VLAN ID also supported (for backward compatibility)

  # Example: Multi-tenant building
  - name: "Building-Tenants"
    entries:
      - name: "Tenant-1"
        psk: "Tenant1Pass2024!"
        vlan: "100"
      - name: "Tenant-2"
        psk: "Tenant2Pass2024!"
        vlan: "101"
      - name: "Tenant-3"
        psk: "Tenant3Pass2024!"
        vlan: "102"
      - name: "Common-Areas"
        psk: "CommonPass2024!"
        vlan: "200"

# Field Descriptions:
#
# name: PPSK profile name (used when creating WiFi SSIDs)
# entries: List of PPSK entries (different passwords for different VLANs)
#   - name: Entry name (descriptive, helps identify the purpose)
#   - psk: Password for this entry
#     - Minimum 8 characters
#     - Must meet WPA2/WPA3 requirements
#     - Use strong, unique passwords
#   - vlan: VLAN name or ID to assign (optional)
#     - VLAN NAME (recommended): References network name from infra_networks.yml
#       - Example: "Trusted", "IoT", "Guest"
#       - Automatically resolved to VLAN ID
#       - Single source of truth - change VLAN ID in one place
#     - VLAN ID (backward compatible): Direct VLAN number
#       - Example: "10", "20", "30"
#       - Can be string or integer
#     - If omitted, uses SSID's default VLAN
#   - mac: MAC address restriction (optional, advanced use)
#     - Usually left empty ("")
#     - Can restrict specific MAC to this password/VLAN
#
# How PPSK Works:
# ===============
# 1. Create a PPSK profile with multiple password entries
# 2. Each password can optionally assign devices to a specific VLAN
# 3. Create a WiFi SSID that references the PPSK profile
# 4. Users see one SSID but are placed on different VLANs based on their password
# 5. The SSID appears the same to all users - only the password differs
#
# Benefits:
# =========
# - Simplified WiFi management (one SSID instead of many)
# - Network segmentation without revealing network structure
# - Easy onboarding (give users appropriate password for their access level)
# - Flexible access control (change VLANs by changing passwords)
# - User-friendly (users don't need to select different SSIDs)
#
# Use Cases:
# ==========
# - Multi-tenant networks (apartments, office buildings, coworking spaces)
# - Device type segmentation (IoT devices, smartphones, laptops)
# - Access level management (admin, employee, contractor, guest)
# - Temporary access (time-limited passwords for visitors)
# - Family networks (kids vs. parents with different access)
# - Department-based access in enterprises
#
# Limitations:
# ============
# - PPSK doesn't support 6GHz band (only 2.4GHz and 5GHz)
# - Passwords are known to users (not suitable for high-security environments)
# - Managing many passwords can be complex
# - Password sharing reduces security
#
# Security Best Practices:
# ========================
# - Use strong, unique passwords for each entry
# - Regularly rotate passwords (especially guest passwords)
# - Consider WPA3-Personal for better security
# - Use firewall rules to restrict inter-VLAN communication
# - Monitor for password sharing across VLANs
# - Document who has which password
# - Use expiration for temporary access passwords
#
# Usage in SSID Configuration:
# =============================
# In wireless_ssids.yml, reference the profile:
#
#   wifi_ssids:
#     - name: "MyNetwork"
#       ppsk_profile: "Home-PPSK"  # Reference the PPSK profile
#       enabled: true
#       broadcast_ssid: true
#       guest_network: true  # Usually true for PPSK SSIDs
#       # NO password field - passwords come from PPSK profile
#       # NO vlan field - VLANs assigned per password
#
# Advanced Example - MAC-based PPSK:
# ===================================
# You can restrict specific MACs to use only certain passwords:
#
#   ppsk_profiles:
#     - name: "Restricted-Access"
#       entries:
#         - name: "Server-Access"
#           psk: "ServerPass123!"
#           vlan: "10"
#           mac: "aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff"  # Only this MAC can use this password
#
# Note: Most use cases don't need MAC restriction (leave mac as "")
#
# Auto-Cleanup Feature:
# =====================
# PPSK profiles not defined in this file will be automatically deleted
# if you enable auto-cleanup in your playbook:
#
#   vars:
#     omada_auto_cleanup: true
#
# Benefits:
# - Keeps your configuration in sync with reality
# - Removes orphaned profiles automatically
# - Ensures only defined profiles exist
# - Helps maintain clean configuration
#
# To enable cleanup, set omada_auto_cleanup: true in:
# - Playbook vars
# - Group vars (group_vars/all/00_controller.yml)
# - Host vars
#
# VLAN Name Resolution:
# =====================
# Use VLAN names instead of IDs for better maintainability:
#
# ✓ Recommended (VLAN name):
#   vlan: "Trusted"    # References network name
#
# ✓ Also works (VLAN ID):
#   vlan: "10"         # Direct VLAN ID
#   vlan: 10           # Integer also works
#
# Benefits of using VLAN names:
# - Change VLAN ID in one place (infra_networks.yml)
# - More readable configuration
# - Less error-prone
# - Self-documenting
